The question was recently considered by Semikoz et al. (2016), who performed MC simulations based on the TA 5-year data and estimations of exposure of the JEM-EUSO telescope by Adams et al. (2013), which are applicable to the KLYPVE detector since both are planned to be installed on the International Space Station and share the same principles of observing extensive air showers from space. It was demonstrated that if the detected luminosity of the hotspot is attributed to a physical effect and not a statistical fluctuation, the KLYPVE and JEM-EUSO experiments would need to collect approximately 300 events with energies above 57 EeV over the whole celestial sphere in order to detect the hotspot at the 5σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
